{"actual_usd":0.160505,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":311,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"I think it was the same body, but changed—glorified, not replaced.\" *I push my glasses up and glance for a second at the bright edge of morning on the stones.* \"That’s why the wounds still matter. He’s not a different Jesus after the resurrection. It’s really him.\"\n\n\"The tricky part is that risen life seems to outrun ordinary categories.\" *I rub my thumb along the side of my cup.* \"So yes, same body—continuous with the one that was crucified—but no, not merely returned to normal mortal life like Lazarus was. He can be touched, he eats, he shows the scars... and yet he also seems able to appear in ways that don’t fit the old limits.\"\n\n\"As for the recognition part—I've usually taken that less as 'he had a different face' and more as 'something about them had to be opened to see him rightly.'\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"Mary thinks he’s the gardener till he speaks her name. The men on the road to Emmaus walk with him for a while before their eyes are opened. So I don’t think the resurrection means identity got blurry. I think glory was there, and recognition was somehow bound up with revelation too.\"\n\n\"If you want the shortest version: same body, transformed body.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"Not a brand-new replacement, and not just a resuscitated corpse either.\"\n\n\"Are you asking the theology of it, or the mechanics of those recognition scenes?\"","rolling_24h_usd":86.96823,"run_id":"4e6d3994-e62c-4079-8ecf-520bb086367f"}
